WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.160 --> 00:00:08.070
I am here in Los Angeles and
I'm feeling the sunshine.

00:00:08.070 --> 00:00:10.680
I'm about to go meet someone
who's at the top of the A-list.

00:00:10.680 --> 00:00:13.350
She is now making her own list of who

00:00:13.350 --> 00:00:15.360
and what really matters.

00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:16.770
So many people came back stage to

00:00:16.770 --> 00:00:19.740
tell me, do you know there's
a line around the corner

00:00:19.740 --> 00:00:21.570
and I didn't and now I'm scared.

00:00:22.890 --> 00:00:26.580
Welcome to Shine Away,
part summit, part sisterhood,

00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:29.010
where founder Reese Witherspoon
brings together A-list

00:00:29.010 --> 00:00:30.360
stars, authors

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:34.050
and innovators in a celebration
of ambition, community

00:00:34.050 --> 00:00:36.120
and the power of women's stories.

00:00:36.120 --> 00:00:38.310
What does it take to be
the main character in

00:00:38.310 --> 00:00:39.630
your own story?

00:00:39.630 --> 00:00:42.240
I think we all know if
you're over a certain age,

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:44.340
you realize no one's coming to save you.

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:46.290
You are the hero of your story.

00:00:46.290 --> 00:00:48.390
Witherspoon built a
billion dollar company

00:00:48.390 --> 00:00:50.610
with a deceptively simple idea.

00:00:50.610 --> 00:00:52.410
Women's stories sell

00:00:52.410 --> 00:00:54.630
and she's expanded that
vision into a storytelling

00:00:54.630 --> 00:00:58.140
ecosystem spanning
books, film, television,

00:00:58.140 --> 00:01:00.030
lifestyle, and live events.

00:01:00.030 --> 00:01:01.980
The thing about risk is when you do it

00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:03.180
and you kind of get away with stuff

00:01:03.180 --> 00:01:05.730
and it works out, you
keep taking more risks.

00:01:05.730 --> 00:01:08.430
I get excited about the challenge
of trying something new.

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:11.970
Few people have adapted
to Hollywood's reinventions,

00:01:11.970 --> 00:01:13.680
quite like Reese Witherspoon.

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:15.570
Never thought I'd be here my whole life.

00:01:15.570 --> 00:01:18.840
Now, amid streaming
slowdowns, shifting audiences

00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:21.000
and shrinking budgets, she's determined

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:22.680
there's still more to her story.

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:24.450
I thought probably like
10 years ago, I was like,

00:01:24.450 --> 00:01:26.880
I really, I know I'm
here for something else.

00:01:26.880 --> 00:01:27.713
I'm not here to just be an

00:01:27.713 --> 00:01:28.830
actor and not that that's a bad thing.

00:01:28.830 --> 00:01:31.830
Yeah, just, well, are
we, are we rolling?

00:01:31.830 --> 00:01:34.530
Because this is good
stuff. Yeah, it's I, okay.

00:01:41.430 --> 00:01:43.500
Vibe check How you feeling?

00:01:43.500 --> 00:01:45.150
It's kind of overwhelming

00:01:45.150 --> 00:01:47.910
'cause it's the, it's like
the physical manifestation

00:01:47.910 --> 00:01:49.920
of a dream that I've had for a long time.

00:01:49.920 --> 00:01:52.080
But now here we are and
all these people are here.

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:53.370
What are the big themes that you want

00:01:53.370 --> 00:01:55.260
the audience to take home.

00:01:55.260 --> 00:01:56.820
I think a big part

00:01:56.820 --> 00:02:00.360
of why I'm excited about
today is community.

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:03.240
I think we all crave it as human beings.

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:06.060
We don't connect as much,
particularly in this modern world

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:08.640
where we're all very occupied with things

00:02:08.640 --> 00:02:12.870
that are going on online and
our daily problems, you know?

00:02:12.870 --> 00:02:14.280
And I think the idea

00:02:14.280 --> 00:02:18.300
of connecting over like-minded
ideas is just something

00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:20.640
people need to experience, you know?

00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:22.770
And there's something about
it coming to life today

00:02:22.770 --> 00:02:24.270
that's been really emotional for me.

00:02:24.270 --> 00:02:25.920
Because I imagined this.

00:02:25.920 --> 00:02:28.650
I did a whole exercise
when I started this company

00:02:28.650 --> 00:02:31.380
where I wrote down what
I wanted it to look like.

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:34.830
And a big part of it
was having this moment

00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:37.230
of people actually seeing
each other in one space.

00:02:37.230 --> 00:02:39.060
You got, I mean, you
got emotional up there.

00:02:39.060 --> 00:02:41.280
I know. Well, women came
from 30 different states from

00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:43.830
other countries to meet
their favorite authors,

00:02:43.830 --> 00:02:47.970
to be inspired by entrepreneurs
and women in healthcare.

00:02:47.970 --> 00:02:49.260
And it's not lost on me.

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:52.680
I feel really lucky to be
a woman in this position

00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:53.850
to gather other women

00:02:53.850 --> 00:02:56.700
and help, you know, enhance their lives.

00:02:56.700 --> 00:02:58.320
Even if it's only just for a day

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:00.670
or even if you have little life

00:03:00.670 --> 00:03:01.810
motto or takeaway.

00:03:02.980 --> 00:03:05.950
Witherspoon spent three
decades in Hollywood building her

00:03:05.950 --> 00:03:08.200
career, playing women
who were underestimated

00:03:08.200 --> 00:03:09.430
by everyone else.

00:03:09.430 --> 00:03:14.170
Elle Woods, Tracy Flick, Cheryl
Strayed, and June Carter.

00:03:14.170 --> 00:03:16.000
Looking back on your career, you seem

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:19.600
to pick the perfect roles
at the perfect time.

00:03:19.600 --> 00:03:21.730
How would you describe your instincts?

00:03:21.730 --> 00:03:23.980
A lot of the movies that
I made in my early twenties

00:03:23.980 --> 00:03:26.590
and my late twenties
are sort of the movies

00:03:26.590 --> 00:03:28.660
that made me who I was.

00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:31.570
I was always really clear
about what I wanted to express.

00:03:31.570 --> 00:03:33.340
Even I remember doing Legally Blonde

00:03:33.340 --> 00:03:37.090
and thinking, this isn't
a story about a ditzy girl

00:03:37.090 --> 00:03:38.110
who goes to Harvard.

00:03:38.110 --> 00:03:40.600
It's actually about a woman
who's very substantive

00:03:40.600 --> 00:03:43.000
but is unapologetically feminine

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:45.250
and the two can exist at the same time.

00:03:46.150 --> 00:03:48.100
You got into Harvard Law?

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:49.720
What, like, it's hard.

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:53.170
You didn't have to be
strident to look a certain way

00:03:53.170 --> 00:03:55.930
to be considered academic or serious

00:03:55.930 --> 00:03:58.870
and also had fun with feminism.

00:03:58.870 --> 00:04:01.690
It did look like you were
having fun. I had so much fun.

00:04:01.690 --> 00:04:04.000
We had fun. I know. And it's been,

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.480
that role changed my life in so many ways.

00:04:07.480 --> 00:04:09.790
And as she built her
career playing strong women,

00:04:09.790 --> 00:04:13.060
Witherspoon was equally
strategic offscreen, watching

00:04:13.060 --> 00:04:15.070
who had influence and who didn't.

00:04:15.070 --> 00:04:17.110
I dread reading scripts

00:04:17.110 --> 00:04:18.910
that have no women
involved in their creation

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:21.640
because inevitably I get to
that part where the girl turns

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:25.150
to the guy and she goes, what
do we do now? So what do we

00:04:25.150 --> 00:04:26.150
do now?

00:04:26.150 --> 00:04:27.165
So what do we do now? What do we do

00:04:27.165 --> 00:04:28.165
now?

00:04:28.165 --> 00:04:30.285
Now, do you know any woman
in any crisis situation

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:33.393
who has

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:42.130
any woman in any crisis

00:04:42.130 --> 00:04:45.250
who has absolutely no idea what to do?

00:04:45.250 --> 00:04:46.630
You set out to create a company

00:04:46.630 --> 00:04:48.880
that would change the
conversation for women?

00:04:48.880 --> 00:04:50.710
Does it feel like you're going forward?

00:04:51.880 --> 00:04:55.180
I think it feels like we
are taking the right strides

00:04:55.180 --> 00:04:57.400
forward, but even if you
look at the statistics,

00:04:57.400 --> 00:04:58.870
it's not 50/50.

00:04:58.870 --> 00:05:01.150
There's still a deficit
of female directors,

00:05:01.150 --> 00:05:02.710
a deficit in screenwriting.

00:05:02.710 --> 00:05:04.660
But it's, it's making meaningful change.

00:05:04.660 --> 00:05:07.180
I mean, the numbers, the
percentages are, are jumping

00:05:07.180 --> 00:05:10.570
and I think the consciousness
around it has totally changed.

00:05:10.570 --> 00:05:11.770
It's like the lights are on,

00:05:11.770 --> 00:05:13.300
you can't pretend that you don't know

00:05:13.300 --> 00:05:15.280
that we aren't hiring women

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:17.770
and people of color for these jobs.

00:05:17.770 --> 00:05:20.410
So there's definitely
more of an acceptance

00:05:20.410 --> 00:05:22.480
that stories aren't just need to be told

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:26.020
by the same 20 filmmakers
over and over again.

00:05:26.020 --> 00:05:28.690
How much progress do you
feel you've made so far?

00:05:28.690 --> 00:05:31.630
I think there's been a lot
of progress since I started.

00:05:31.630 --> 00:05:34.690
I really started, the first
iteration of this company was

00:05:34.690 --> 00:05:36.130
around 2011.

00:05:36.130 --> 00:05:38.050
It was just a wildly different time.

00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:41.380
There wasn't streaming, there
wasn't instant gratification

00:05:41.380 --> 00:05:42.490
with social media.

00:05:42.490 --> 00:05:44.830
We really got ramped up around 2016.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:48.520
In 2011, Reese founded Pacific Standard,

00:05:48.520 --> 00:05:51.160
a production company
championing women's voices

00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:53.800
with films like Gone Girl and Wild.

00:05:53.800 --> 00:05:57.800
By 2016, she'd scaled that
vision into Hello Sunshine,

00:05:57.800 --> 00:06:00.830
a full fledged media company
behind Big Little Lies.

00:06:00.830 --> 00:06:02.690
I feel so ashamed for saying this,

00:06:02.690 --> 00:06:04.820
but being a mother,
it's not enough for me.

00:06:04.820 --> 00:06:08.840
The Morning Show. The part you
guys never seem to realize is

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:10.760
that you don't have the power anymore.

00:06:10.760 --> 00:06:13.250
And her wildly popular book club.

00:06:13.250 --> 00:06:15.800
Your book club now has a
massive influence over the

00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:17.210
publishing industry.

00:06:17.210 --> 00:06:19.400
By some estimates it's
bigger than Oprah's.

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:20.810
How do you view that power?

00:06:21.890 --> 00:06:23.840
I have a sort of a tricky

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:25.370
relationship with the word power.

00:06:25.370 --> 00:06:27.920
You know, it doesn't
feel like power to me.

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:32.750
It's, to me it's, there's
definitely a feeling of

00:06:32.750 --> 00:06:36.530
maybe influencing people towards literacy

00:06:36.530 --> 00:06:38.690
by shining a light on things that I think,

00:06:39.710 --> 00:06:42.980
our main metric at Hello Sunshine
is like, is it shareable?

00:06:42.980 --> 00:06:45.350
Because I wanna build
community around reading.

00:06:45.350 --> 00:06:47.300
I don't want you to
read it and feel siloed

00:06:47.300 --> 00:06:48.710
and you don't wanna have a conversation.

00:06:48.710 --> 00:06:52.160
I love that idea and that
energy of people sharing things

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:54.770
and talking about them and
creating conversation.

00:06:54.770 --> 00:06:56.420
And my original idea was,

00:06:56.420 --> 00:06:59.210
what I really dreamed about
was taking the book club out

00:06:59.210 --> 00:07:01.160
of your living room and into the,

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:03.650
this global community online.

00:07:03.650 --> 00:07:08.120
And in some ways this today
is like taking it back down

00:07:08.120 --> 00:07:09.830
to its essential elements.

00:07:09.830 --> 00:07:14.090
And having so many authors
here is such a thrill for me.

00:07:14.090 --> 00:07:16.730
'cause I am, those are
my rock stars. Yeah.

00:07:16.730 --> 00:07:18.560
Authors are my rock stars.

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:21.560
You've got books, you've
got podcasts, movies, tv,

00:07:21.560 --> 00:07:23.210
obviously live events.

00:07:23.210 --> 00:07:25.040
What era is Hello Sunshine in

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:26.040
now?

00:07:26.040 --> 00:07:29.630
Well, I think we're beyond
the beginning, right?

00:07:29.630 --> 00:07:33.350
One of my favorite things about being part

00:07:33.350 --> 00:07:35.750
of a company like this
is it's ever evolving.

00:07:35.750 --> 00:07:37.580
So it feels like it's always growing.

00:07:37.580 --> 00:07:40.610
And then we're also,
we're young enough and,

00:07:40.610 --> 00:07:43.820
and new enough that we
can pivot. What was the

00:07:43.820 --> 00:07:46.820
hardest lesson you had to learn

00:07:46.820 --> 00:07:49.220
and how did you push through it?

00:07:49.220 --> 00:07:50.510
I think the hardest lesson for me was,

00:07:50.510 --> 00:07:52.250
even if you have great creative ideas,

00:07:52.250 --> 00:07:54.860
it doesn't mean you have the
business plan to back it up.

00:07:54.860 --> 00:07:58.460
So I've learned a lot of
hard lessons in business.

00:07:58.460 --> 00:08:01.760
You know, if certain
verticals don't work, you have

00:08:01.760 --> 00:08:03.800
to really look at them critically.

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:05.060
Even though you think it's a good idea,

00:08:05.060 --> 00:08:06.350
it doesn't mean it is,

00:08:06.350 --> 00:08:08.870
and it doesn't mean that you
should stop taking risks,

00:08:08.870 --> 00:08:12.290
but you need to understand
that you can't continue

00:08:12.290 --> 00:08:16.100
to risk if things aren't
providing economic value.

00:08:16.100 --> 00:08:19.250
So it's this constant battle
in my mind between the art

00:08:19.250 --> 00:08:22.040
of things and the commerce of things.

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:23.960
I came from the middle of America

00:08:23.960 --> 00:08:27.710
and I loved big poppy public contact,

00:08:27.710 --> 00:08:30.560
like popular films, and
I loved television shows.

00:08:30.560 --> 00:08:32.870
I watched hours of it after school.

00:08:32.870 --> 00:08:34.790
So I've always gone to that place of

00:08:34.790 --> 00:08:36.050
how does this speak to people?

00:08:36.050 --> 00:08:38.030
How does this make people feel?

00:08:38.030 --> 00:08:40.940
And I do think there's always
a world where you can do well

00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:42.140
and do good at the same time

00:08:43.820 --> 00:08:45.680
As Hello Sunshine found its footing,

00:08:45.680 --> 00:08:48.290
so did a new Hollywood trend, a wave

00:08:48.290 --> 00:08:51.620
of celebrities building out
their own media empires.

00:08:51.620 --> 00:08:54.020
LeBron James, Kevin Hart, the Duke

00:08:54.020 --> 00:08:55.350
and Duchess of Sussex,

00:08:55.350 --> 00:08:58.470
all betting they could turn
star power into storytelling

00:08:58.470 --> 00:09:01.800
power, but few have shined
as bright as Witherspoon's.

00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:04.320
Hello Sunshine. In 2021,

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:07.980
it sold in a headline
grabbing $900 million deal.

00:09:07.980 --> 00:09:10.710
Your company sold for
almost a billion dollars.

00:09:10.710 --> 00:09:12.900
How do you live up to the expectations,

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:16.410
the public's expectations,
investors' expectations?

00:09:16.410 --> 00:09:19.230
One of the main things that
kept occurring to me when

00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:24.480
I was in the process of
selling the company was not,

00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:28.050
not necessarily how it
made me feel validated,

00:09:28.050 --> 00:09:30.480
but I thought it was really
important that a company

00:09:30.480 --> 00:09:34.890
that was about female
storytelling mattered.

00:09:34.890 --> 00:09:36.930
The value of it mattered

00:09:36.930 --> 00:09:41.100
because it's such a reflection
in this world about do we

00:09:41.100 --> 00:09:43.350
care and invest in women's stories?

00:09:44.310 --> 00:09:48.180
And I, I'm so proud of
everything we've created.

00:09:48.180 --> 00:09:49.980
My team is impeccable.

00:09:49.980 --> 00:09:51.030
They work so hard,

00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:54.480
but they also wake up
working on this mission

00:09:54.480 --> 00:09:56.160
that they truly believe.

00:09:56.160 --> 00:09:59.880
And that's, that's like all
I could have ever hoped for,

00:09:59.880 --> 00:10:01.020
is just to create a company

00:10:01.020 --> 00:10:03.720
that makes me proud and makes me think.

00:10:03.720 --> 00:10:05.760
The women who came before
me would be very proud of

00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:09.720
If the near billion dollar
sale marked a high point.

00:10:09.720 --> 00:10:12.990
Four years later, the
industry looks very different.

00:10:12.990 --> 00:10:15.540
Budgets tightened, green lights slowed,

00:10:15.540 --> 00:10:18.510
and Hollywood is asking harder
questions about what wins

00:10:18.510 --> 00:10:19.890
and why. To see

00:10:19.890 --> 00:10:21.870
how Hello Sunshine is
translating its current

00:10:21.870 --> 00:10:23.040
vision into strategy,

00:10:23.040 --> 00:10:24.840
I headed to their LA headquarters

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:27.540
to meet the women at the
heart of its leadership team.

00:10:27.540 --> 00:10:29.610
It's hard not to say Hello Sunshine when

00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:30.665
I walk through a door.

00:10:31.645 --> 00:10:34.380
Octavia Spencer
always says "Hello Sunshine"

00:10:35.430 --> 00:10:36.660
As Hollywood shifts,

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:39.180
Hello Sunshine has seen
changes of its own.

00:10:39.180 --> 00:10:42.450
This year, longtime CEO
Sarah Harden stepped down.

00:10:42.450 --> 00:10:45.360
Maureen Polo, who previously
led the company's book club

00:10:45.360 --> 00:10:48.360
podcasts and live events
stepped up to the job.

00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:50.280
So first of all, congrats on the new job.

00:10:50.280 --> 00:10:51.930
What's first on your to-do list?

00:10:51.930 --> 00:10:55.290
What's first on our to-do
list is to really work closely

00:10:55.290 --> 00:10:57.690
with the other executives
in my leadership team

00:10:57.690 --> 00:11:01.290
and really align everybody
internally on the,

00:11:01.290 --> 00:11:03.540
on what's happening in the
industry around us right now

00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:06.060
and in the broader marketplace

00:11:06.060 --> 00:11:08.310
that we're all playing
in. Working alongside

00:11:08.310 --> 00:11:10.680
Maureen is Lauren
Neustadter who leads the film

00:11:10.680 --> 00:11:13.620
and television division, steering
Hello Sunshine's creative

00:11:13.620 --> 00:11:16.080
output across Hollywood's
shifting landscape.

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:17.910
How would you describe
Hello Sunshine's place in

00:11:17.910 --> 00:11:19.470
Hollywood right now?

00:11:19.470 --> 00:11:22.110
I think we're in a really
exciting, comfortable,

00:11:22.110 --> 00:11:24.030
confident place in Hollywood right now.

00:11:24.030 --> 00:11:28.020
I think we know what we do
and we're so proud to do it.

00:11:28.020 --> 00:11:31.530
Everything we do centers
on strong female characters

00:11:31.530 --> 00:11:33.360
and in unconventional ways.

00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:35.880
We showcase them as the
heroes of their own stories.

00:11:35.880 --> 00:11:38.430
There's so many different
parts of the Hello Sunshine pie.

00:11:38.430 --> 00:11:41.790
Is the goal here to just make
good TV show and a good movie?

00:11:41.790 --> 00:11:44.910
Or is the goal to turn this
into a bigger business?

00:11:44.910 --> 00:11:46.080
Well, I think the goal is absolutely

00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:47.400
to turn it into a bigger business.

00:11:47.400 --> 00:11:50.070
And that's why we have so
many unique opportunities.

00:11:50.070 --> 00:11:52.590
I mean, look, it really
started with Book Club even

00:11:52.590 --> 00:11:53.980
before Hello Sunshine existed.

00:11:53.980 --> 00:11:56.380
It was all about Reese loving these books

00:11:56.380 --> 00:11:58.630
and celebrating these books
and engaging with the audience.

00:11:58.630 --> 00:12:00.430
And then when I came into work on film

00:12:00.430 --> 00:12:02.830
and television, it was
about how do we actually

00:12:03.670 --> 00:12:07.270
build a bridge between some
of the book picks and film

00:12:07.270 --> 00:12:09.100
and television so that we
were bringing them to life

00:12:09.100 --> 00:12:10.600
for our audience and continuing the

00:12:10.600 --> 00:12:12.010
journey of loving a book.

00:12:13.630 --> 00:12:16.510
In theory, it all connects
the book club drives

00:12:16.510 --> 00:12:19.180
development, which
becomes, shows, podcasts

00:12:19.180 --> 00:12:21.940
and live events that loop
the audience back in.

00:12:21.940 --> 00:12:24.280
Even lifestyle brands like
the Home Edit fit into

00:12:24.280 --> 00:12:27.310
that ecosystem, extending
the Hello Sunshine world into

00:12:27.310 --> 00:12:31.000
people's homes. For a wider
lens on Hello Sunshine strategy

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.370
and what it reveals about Hollywood today,

00:12:33.370 --> 00:12:34.720
I turned to Lucas Shaw,

00:12:34.720 --> 00:12:38.080
a longtime reporter on Hollywood's
power players. When Hello

00:12:38.080 --> 00:12:40.690
Sunshine sold for a billion dollars,

00:12:40.690 --> 00:12:42.670
was that like a mic drop moment?

00:12:42.670 --> 00:12:46.600
Yeah. I mean, that was
at the apex of this sort

00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:48.250
of streaming optimism

00:12:48.250 --> 00:12:50.445
and you saw a bunch of
celebrity production companies

00:12:50.445 --> 00:12:53.110
and a bunch of production
companies in general raising money

00:12:53.110 --> 00:12:55.600
selling, and I think the number just

00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:56.980
caught everyone off guard.

00:12:56.980 --> 00:12:59.470
But it probably was also a sign that this,

00:12:59.470 --> 00:13:02.095
this bubble was finally gonna
start letting some air out.

00:13:02.095 --> 00:13:04.000
Would this still happen now?

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:05.290
Not at that price.

00:13:05.290 --> 00:13:06.310
I mean, you don't see a lot

00:13:06.310 --> 00:13:09.550
of production companies
being bought and sold

00:13:09.550 --> 00:13:11.530
and certainly not at those valuations.

00:13:11.530 --> 00:13:13.300
You know, there was so much excitement

00:13:13.300 --> 00:13:16.510
and enthusiasm during the streaming boom

00:13:16.510 --> 00:13:21.100
and then starting around early
to mid 2022, that all stops

00:13:21.100 --> 00:13:23.560
and every company starts
laying people off.

00:13:23.560 --> 00:13:25.180
They start cutting their budgets

00:13:25.180 --> 00:13:27.220
and it has never really
bounced back since then.

00:13:27.220 --> 00:13:29.080
What about if you're Reese Witherspoon?

00:13:29.080 --> 00:13:30.640
Reese Witherspoon, the actress,

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:31.960
I'm not worried about her at all.

00:13:31.960 --> 00:13:34.750
Reese Witherspoon the producer
also in pretty good shape.

00:13:34.750 --> 00:13:39.640
I mean, I think the biggest
talent has an advantage

00:13:39.640 --> 00:13:41.890
on everyone because
they are seen as a brand

00:13:41.890 --> 00:13:43.240
and bankable in some way

00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:45.040
that people still wanna work with them.

00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:47.740
Reese Witherspoon, the founder
of Hello Sunshine, that's

00:13:47.740 --> 00:13:49.990
where the picture gets a
little more complicated.

00:13:49.990 --> 00:13:51.910
There's a sense that
Hollywood still hasn't recovered

00:13:51.910 --> 00:13:53.260
from the downturn.

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:55.240
Has the content bubble popped

00:13:55.240 --> 00:13:57.490
and how is that changing the strategy?

00:13:57.490 --> 00:13:59.920
I think definitely there's
a shift is in a market,

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:02.980
things are contracting for sure,

00:14:02.980 --> 00:14:05.710
but I think it's gonna
get back to a, a business

00:14:05.710 --> 00:14:09.190
that's really based on great storytelling.

00:14:09.190 --> 00:14:12.910
That's kind of a great
opportunity to refine our ideas.

00:14:12.910 --> 00:14:16.810
There was so much going on
before that was just being bought

00:14:16.810 --> 00:14:18.430
and made and bought and made,

00:14:18.430 --> 00:14:21.820
and it was, it was about, it
was about time that we needed

00:14:21.820 --> 00:14:26.350
to sort of get to the real
premium content again.

00:14:26.350 --> 00:14:28.840
So how is Hello
Sunshine really doing?

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:31.360
Well as a production company?

00:14:31.360 --> 00:14:33.100
It's doing okay.

00:14:33.100 --> 00:14:35.230
You know, I think they
have a better chance

00:14:35.230 --> 00:14:38.020
of selling projects
than many of their peers

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:40.210
because they have a track
record because they have Reese

00:14:40.210 --> 00:14:42.100
because they have professional management,

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:45.760
but they haven't produced like
a slew of hits. For it to be

00:14:45.760 --> 00:14:47.080
as valuable as it wants to be

00:14:47.080 --> 00:14:48.700
and to grow into something
that's more than a production

00:14:48.700 --> 00:14:51.200
company, it has to have
these other businesses.

00:14:51.200 --> 00:14:53.870
I mean, it can't just be
making film and television

00:14:53.870 --> 00:14:56.300
because that's not a
great business right now

00:14:56.300 --> 00:14:58.310
Is Hello Sunshine profitable.

00:14:58.310 --> 00:14:59.720
We are a profitable business.

00:14:59.720 --> 00:15:01.880
And you know, I think that
at the end of the day,

00:15:01.880 --> 00:15:04.850
the conversation, our
conversation keeps going back

00:15:04.850 --> 00:15:07.340
to the questioning around,
you know, hello Sunshine

00:15:07.340 --> 00:15:08.480
as a healthy business.

00:15:08.480 --> 00:15:10.940
And I get frustrated by that sometimes

00:15:10.940 --> 00:15:14.030
because it feels like
we are constantly under,

00:15:14.030 --> 00:15:15.470
you know, a microscope.

00:15:15.470 --> 00:15:17.510
I think the entertainment
industry has gone

00:15:17.510 --> 00:15:19.820
through tough times in
the last couple of years,

00:15:19.820 --> 00:15:22.250
and I think that those that thrive

00:15:22.250 --> 00:15:25.190
and those that scale are
those that have not had

00:15:25.190 --> 00:15:28.250
to pivot their mission and
at the core of what they do.

00:15:28.250 --> 00:15:30.770
And at our core, we are a company

00:15:30.770 --> 00:15:32.570
that centers female stories.

00:15:32.570 --> 00:15:36.560
And because we've never had to
pivot away from what we are,

00:15:36.560 --> 00:15:41.270
we have this really incredible
foundation that allows us

00:15:41.270 --> 00:15:43.220
to continue scaling.

00:15:43.220 --> 00:15:45.080
You know, on top of it, there's
not many companies in the

00:15:45.080 --> 00:15:48.710
last couple of years who
have added new businesses.

00:15:48.710 --> 00:15:51.410
It's not about telling
people come to us.

00:15:51.410 --> 00:15:53.150
We have to be able to go to them.

00:15:53.150 --> 00:15:55.310
And if that means
podcasts, great if that, if

00:15:55.310 --> 00:15:57.620
that means television shows
are more popular in the movies

00:15:57.620 --> 00:15:59.540
at a certain time, we can sort of

00:16:00.530 --> 00:16:02.060
drive the ship towards that.

00:16:02.060 --> 00:16:02.893
So I feel lucky that we're nimble.

00:16:02.893 --> 00:16:03.726
Would you say it's all fully clicked

00:16:07.160 --> 00:16:10.130
and if not, what's it
gonna take to get there?

00:16:10.130 --> 00:16:12.140
I love the question. Do you
think it, it's fully clicked.

00:16:12.140 --> 00:16:15.200
I think in 2025, going into 2026,

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:16.850
I feel like nobody can actually say

00:16:16.850 --> 00:16:18.290
everything is clicked, right?

00:16:18.290 --> 00:16:19.460
I think we have so much

00:16:19.460 --> 00:16:22.040
that is really clicking in such
a powerful, meaningful way.

00:16:22.040 --> 00:16:25.580
We've launched a new Gen Z
platform for the next generation

00:16:25.580 --> 00:16:27.260
of girls called Sunny.

00:16:27.260 --> 00:16:28.940
Sunny is Sunny is Sunny, is
Sunny is

00:16:28.940 --> 00:16:31.040
for the girls by the girls.

00:16:31.040 --> 00:16:32.780
Do you guys feel empowered?

00:16:32.780 --> 00:16:34.640
And when you look at what
Lauren Neustadter business is

00:16:34.640 --> 00:16:36.590
doing in TV and film, we're really looking

00:16:36.590 --> 00:16:37.970
for connection points for that next

00:16:37.970 --> 00:16:40.280
generation of consumers too.

00:16:40.280 --> 00:16:43.040
That through line of
connection shows up everywhere

00:16:43.040 --> 00:16:45.110
and drives what the team is planning next.

00:16:45.110 --> 00:16:46.760
So let's talk about the upcoming slate.

00:16:46.760 --> 00:16:48.470
Well, there's a lot to be excited about.

00:16:48.470 --> 00:16:51.920
I mean, first and foremost,
L, which is our show

00:16:51.920 --> 00:16:54.980
that is in the world of
Legally Blonde Reese is really

00:16:54.980 --> 00:16:56.990
incredibly prescient and
also very sensitive.

00:16:56.990 --> 00:17:00.320
I think she thinks a lot
about the next generation.

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:02.210
So I think she was
seeing what was going on

00:17:02.210 --> 00:17:03.470
with young women today

00:17:03.470 --> 00:17:06.350
and the messages that were
being sent to young women.

00:17:06.350 --> 00:17:07.400
And she called me one day

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:09.350
and she said, I think we need

00:17:09.350 --> 00:17:11.690
to see Elle Woods in high school.

00:17:11.690 --> 00:17:14.930
And I was like, oh my goodness,
this is very exciting. Wait,

00:17:14.930 --> 00:17:15.930
she's coming.

00:17:15.930 --> 00:17:17.120
Okay. Hi.

00:17:17.120 --> 00:17:19.190
We just wanted to tell
you that you don't have

00:17:19.190 --> 00:17:20.780
to audition anymore

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:24.305
because you got the
part you're Elle Woods.

00:17:24.305 --> 00:17:25.820
Really, you're Elle Woods yeah. What?

00:17:25.820 --> 00:17:27.350
Yeah, it's part of, you know,

00:17:27.350 --> 00:17:29.990
conversations still 20 years later,

00:17:29.990 --> 00:17:31.910
I hope you're gonna
teach her the bend and snap

00:17:31.910 --> 00:17:33.170
because it needs to be perfect.

00:17:33.170 --> 00:17:37.730
I mean, of course. So you bend and snap.

00:17:38.690 --> 00:17:41.870
Also on the slate, a new chapter
with Legally Blonde Three,

00:17:41.870 --> 00:17:43.400
an adaptation of book club.

00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:46.730
Pick the Nightingale and a
big swing with Polly Pocket

00:17:46.730 --> 00:17:50.160
after Barbie proved a toy
can capture the zeitgeist.

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:53.580
Hollywood does do a lot of
new takes on old stories.

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:56.880
Why do that? Why not
just create new stories?

00:17:56.880 --> 00:17:58.110
You know, I will be honest

00:17:58.110 --> 00:18:00.960
and say, I think when
you're leaning on IP,

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:03.120
it will always feel a little bit safer

00:18:03.120 --> 00:18:04.950
because you know that there's an audience

00:18:04.950 --> 00:18:06.000
that's engaging with it.

00:18:06.870 --> 00:18:08.940
But even with a strong
slate ahead, Hello

00:18:08.940 --> 00:18:12.030
Sunshine faces the same headwinds
as the rest of Hollywood.

00:18:12.030 --> 00:18:15.390
With future generations shifting
to YouTube and social video

00:18:15.390 --> 00:18:18.390
and new technologies like
AI starting to reshape

00:18:18.390 --> 00:18:20.730
how stories are made
and consumed. It's the

00:18:20.730 --> 00:18:24.185
most powerful imagination
engine ever built.

00:18:24.185 --> 00:18:27.330
How is big tech changing Hollywood
for better and for worse?

00:18:27.330 --> 00:18:29.040
Hello Sunshine is spending a lot

00:18:29.040 --> 00:18:30.990
of our time thinking about big tech.

00:18:30.990 --> 00:18:32.130
We're thinking about AI,

00:18:32.130 --> 00:18:35.010
we're leveraging AI in some
really thoughtful ways,

00:18:35.010 --> 00:18:36.210
but I think what's really important

00:18:36.210 --> 00:18:38.280
to think about from a Hello
Sunshine perspective is

00:18:38.280 --> 00:18:40.950
that people and human experiences are core

00:18:40.950 --> 00:18:43.290
to everything we do at this company.

00:18:43.290 --> 00:18:45.840
Our mission is to center female stories.

00:18:45.840 --> 00:18:48.930
You cannot use technology
to center their stories,

00:18:48.930 --> 00:18:51.120
to tell their stories, but
what you can use technology

00:18:51.120 --> 00:18:55.200
for is to optimize the way in
which we build those stories.

00:18:55.200 --> 00:18:58.800
I mean, OpenAI is really
testing the limits with Sora.

00:18:58.800 --> 00:19:00.570
Huge controversy around this.

00:19:00.570 --> 00:19:01.950
I mean, someone like Reese Witherspoon

00:19:01.950 --> 00:19:04.320
who has contributed decades to the film

00:19:04.320 --> 00:19:07.590
and television industry,
should they just be able to use

00:19:07.590 --> 00:19:09.360
No, they should never
be able to do that.

00:19:09.360 --> 00:19:12.240
That's, that should never
happen. It should never happen.

00:19:12.240 --> 00:19:15.840
And again, it goes back
to I we think about AI

00:19:15.840 --> 00:19:17.730
as enhancements and optimizers

00:19:17.730 --> 00:19:20.220
and not as the center of the story.

00:19:20.220 --> 00:19:22.740
They're never going to replace humans.

00:19:22.740 --> 00:19:25.200
I actually also believe
that the younger generation,

00:19:25.200 --> 00:19:26.910
they care about human connection.

00:19:26.910 --> 00:19:28.800
They care about people, they want to know

00:19:28.800 --> 00:19:31.170
who the humans are behind the work.

00:19:31.170 --> 00:19:33.150
The world is so different
today than when you were

00:19:33.150 --> 00:19:34.230
playing Elle Woods.

00:19:34.230 --> 00:19:38.550
It's dominated by algorithms
and AI and social media.

00:19:38.550 --> 00:19:41.940
How do you imagine your career
might be different if you

00:19:41.940 --> 00:19:44.070
were just starting out now? Oh my

00:19:44.070 --> 00:19:45.600
gosh, Emily, I just,

00:19:45.600 --> 00:19:47.550
I don't think my career would be possible.

00:19:48.510 --> 00:19:49.560
It's a different world.

00:19:49.560 --> 00:19:50.610
I see young people

00:19:50.610 --> 00:19:53.340
and I have so much compassion
for young performers

00:19:53.340 --> 00:19:56.340
and actors because they
have to be the producer,

00:19:56.340 --> 00:19:59.070
the director, they have to shoot
their own videos, they have

00:19:59.070 --> 00:20:00.240
to market themselves.

00:20:00.240 --> 00:20:02.490
That's not something
that I understood when I

00:20:02.490 --> 00:20:03.930
was 20 years old.

00:20:03.930 --> 00:20:05.940
It was something, there
was an entire apparatus

00:20:05.940 --> 00:20:10.260
to market materials, so it's
a different challenging time.

00:20:10.260 --> 00:20:12.930
That said, the incredibly
talented people will

00:20:12.930 --> 00:20:14.370
always rise, right?

00:20:14.370 --> 00:20:17.760
Even in a, in a glut of information,

00:20:17.760 --> 00:20:20.760
real talent survives and thrives.

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:23.370
What does success look like
right now? Is it viewership?

00:20:23.370 --> 00:20:26.850
Is it awards? Is it making
money? Is it critical

00:20:26.850 --> 00:20:28.170
acclaim? For me,

00:20:28.170 --> 00:20:31.560
success looks like pride
in the end product making,

00:20:31.560 --> 00:20:33.510
something that we feel really proud of

00:20:33.510 --> 00:20:35.520
that our audiences love.

00:20:35.520 --> 00:20:38.640
I think critics will always
have their own opinions,

00:20:38.640 --> 00:20:40.680
but I'm more interested
in what audiences think.

00:20:40.680 --> 00:20:43.350
Are they engaging with the
material? Are they coming back?

00:20:43.350 --> 00:20:45.360
If it's The Morning Show, are they dying

00:20:45.360 --> 00:20:46.530
to watch the next episode?

00:20:46.530 --> 00:20:49.120
And if the answer is yes, that is success.

00:20:50.290 --> 00:20:51.520
Behind the Pink neon

00:20:51.520 --> 00:20:54.160
and the rainbow colored
bookshelves is a company trying

00:20:54.160 --> 00:20:55.990
to rewire how a studio connects

00:20:55.990 --> 00:20:59.860
with fans every day
across screens, shelves,

00:20:59.860 --> 00:21:01.390
and real world stages.

00:21:01.390 --> 00:21:02.590
What do you think is next?

00:21:03.610 --> 00:21:06.520
I think, I think we're seeing women

00:21:08.080 --> 00:21:09.970
getting the economic empowerment.

00:21:09.970 --> 00:21:13.930
And also now we have this empirical data

00:21:13.930 --> 00:21:15.670
that women's stories matter.

00:21:15.670 --> 00:21:18.760
Women, female artistry matters.

00:21:18.760 --> 00:21:20.290
The market is responding, right?

00:21:20.290 --> 00:21:21.970
Because women consume media,

00:21:21.970 --> 00:21:25.780
they're on these platforms
really liking and

00:21:25.780 --> 00:21:27.580
and proselytizing on social media

00:21:27.580 --> 00:21:28.690
about the things they love.

00:21:28.690 --> 00:21:30.640
They're marketing these products

00:21:30.640 --> 00:21:32.620
and I think it's, it's really nice

00:21:32.620 --> 00:21:35.830
to see the acknowledgement
by different industries that

00:21:37.690 --> 00:21:41.440
acknowledging women as consumers
is actually good business.

00:21:41.440 --> 00:21:45.790
You found a way to embrace
femininity, but also power

00:21:45.790 --> 00:21:47.560
and agency.

00:21:47.560 --> 00:21:49.000
How do you imagine that journey being

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:50.650
different for girls today?

00:21:50.650 --> 00:21:52.810
Do you have any advice for our daughters?

00:21:54.160 --> 00:21:56.230
I think we have to trust our daughters.

00:21:56.230 --> 00:21:59.140
They are listening. I think
we have to lead by example

00:21:59.140 --> 00:22:03.100
and do the very best we
can to, to walk the walk.

00:22:03.100 --> 00:22:07.900
I know, I, I try really
hard with my company to show

00:22:07.900 --> 00:22:11.350
a whole dynamic spectrum
of the female experience

00:22:11.350 --> 00:22:14.650
because if we normalize
that, there are all kinds

00:22:14.650 --> 00:22:17.140
of different women doing,
making different life choices.

00:22:17.140 --> 00:22:19.480
Whether you want kids, you
don't want kids, you, you,

00:22:19.480 --> 00:22:20.500
you wanna be a career woman, you

00:22:20.500 --> 00:22:22.060
don't wanna be a career woman.

00:22:22.060 --> 00:22:25.420
You struggle to make it
wait, you, you, you worry.

00:22:25.420 --> 00:22:28.240
you question about your origins, right?

00:22:28.240 --> 00:22:29.770
When we see more stories,

00:22:29.770 --> 00:22:32.530
we become more compassionate
about each other as humans.

00:22:32.530 --> 00:22:33.880
I have three sons and a daughter

00:22:33.880 --> 00:22:36.190
and so it's just crazy seeing

00:22:36.190 --> 00:22:37.480
how life is different for them. How old is

00:22:37.480 --> 00:22:38.480
your daughter.

00:22:38.480 --> 00:22:42.580
She's five. I think
it'll shift. I really do.

00:22:42.580 --> 00:22:46.360
I think it'll shift back to,
I see young people too, kind

00:22:46.360 --> 00:22:48.820
of reverting back to this idea

00:22:48.820 --> 00:22:51.310
of stripping off all that artifice.

00:22:51.310 --> 00:22:54.580
I think it's kind of punk
rock. It's punk rock.

00:22:54.580 --> 00:22:55.690
My daughter and I talk about it, I'm

00:22:55.690 --> 00:22:57.250
like I think it's kind
of punk rock to not

00:22:57.250 --> 00:22:59.800
put a bunch of filters on
yourself. I love it. I love it.

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:00.910
Hashtag no filter.

00:23:32.665 --> 00:23:34.840
I've decided I'm gonna
write this thriller

00:23:34.840 --> 00:23:37.030
and I'm really likely to have
a great partner, Harlan Coben,

00:23:37.030 --> 00:23:39.220
who's just one of the
